  "prompt": "What is the penalty for driving without insurance in Texas?",
  "response": "In Texas, driving without insurance can lead to significant penalties. First-time offenders can face fines ranging from $175 to $350. Subsequent offenses can result in fines between $350 and $1,000. Additionally, drivers may also have their vehicle impounded, incur court costs, and face license suspension or revocation. To reinstate your license, you might be required to file an SR-22 form, which is a certificate of financial responsibility that proves you have purchased the minimum required insurance coverage. Moreover, driving without insurance puts you at risk of personal financial losses if you are involved in an accident.",
